<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Triantha occidentalis </i>grows in California and southern Oregon in montane and subalpine elevations in wet meadows and fens. It has short rhizomes, linear grasslike leaves, and a densely glandular peduncle that supports a scapose inflorescence of white flowers. Many manuals use the name <i>Tofieldia glutinosa </i>or <i>T. occidentalis </i>for this liliaceous plant. Packer (2002) separated <i>Tofieldia </i>with scapes lacking glands from <i>Triantha </i>with glands. <i>Triantha occidentalis</i>has three subspecies; ssp. <i>occidentalis </i>grows in California. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Narthecium californicum </i>occurs in northern California in coastal sites and montane elevations in wet meadows, fens, and stream banks. It has creeping rhizomes, linear grasslike leaves, and a scapose inflorescence of yellow flowers. <br/>
<br/>
Cooper and Wolf (2006) considered that typical stands in northern California mountains contain both lilies and occur in transitional or intermediate fens based upon their water chemistry. While <i>N. californicum </i>is local in the Sierra Nevada, it appears to be more common than previously thought, and it is not well studied in fens in the Klamath Mountains and in coastal areas. These fens should be more thoroughly investigated. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
