    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The ranges of <i>Triantha occidentalis</i> and <i>Narthecium californicum</i> include Northern California Coast (263A) and Northern California Coast Ranges (M261B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ac-l, An, Ap-r, At-u). Stands of <i>N. californicum, T. occidentalis,</i> or both lilies are extensive in the Siskiyou Mountains and the Trinity Alps at higher elevations. Cooper and Wolf (2006) found stands with both lilies in transitional fens on South Fork Mountain; the species also occur around Cedar Lake in the Cedar Basin RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1982, see Cheng 2004) in the Trinity Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-b, Ed-h). Cooper and Wolf (2006) sampled stands in basin fens and sloping rich fens of low primary production with <i>T. occidentalis,</i> and sloping transitional fens with both lilies in the northern and central parts of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Dj, Dm). Cooper and Wolf (2006) sampled transitional fens with the <i>Triantha occidentalis-Narthecium californicum</i> association in the Lassen National Forest.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Cooper and Wolf (2006) noted that fen vegetation with <i>Narthecium californicum </i>has a limited range in the Sierra Nevada, and stands should be protected. They consider these lily-dominated fens to be unusual from a worldwide perspective. <i>N. californicum </i>causes a liver disease in sheep. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
